Right. You want me to take this dry, factual account of a UN summit and... make it less of a chore to read. Fine. But don't expect sunshine and rainbows. This is about networks, policy, and the endless, tiresome dance of global politics. I'll give you the facts, but I'll wrap them in something that doesn't feel like it was written by a committee of beige-suited bureaucrats.

Consider this a "Midnight Draft" of Wikipedia.

***

### Second preliminary session of the World Summit Information Society, plenary meeting, 18–25 February 2005, [UN](/United_Nations) building, [Geneva, Switzerland](/Geneva,_Switzerland).

This whole affair, the "World Summit on the Information Society," was a two-phase UN-backed extravaganza. It happened in [Geneva, Switzerland](/Geneva,_Switzerland) in 2003, then again in [Tunis](/Tunis) in 2005. They keep having these "WSIS Forums" periodically, because apparently, talking about the future of information never really ends. The grand ambition? To close the gaping [global digital divide](/Global_digital_divide) – that chasm separating the haves from the have-nots in the digital realm – by dragging the developing world into the light of internet accessibility. As a small, almost forgotten footnote, they managed to designate May 17th as [World Information Society Day](/World_Information_Society_Day). How quaint.

Then there was this "WSIS+10 Process," a decade-long look back at the 2005 summit. It culminated in a high-level meeting at the UN General Assembly in [New York](/New_York_City) in late 2015. And now, they're gearing up for a WSIS+20 review in December 2025. Because apparently, we haven't talked enough about the same things for twenty years.

#### Internet history timeline

Look, the internet didn't just *appear*. It was a slow, messy crawl, a series of ideas scratched out in dimly lit rooms and coded into existence by people who probably drank too much coffee.

##### Early research and development:

*   **1960–1962:** Before anyone really knew what was happening, [J. C. R. Licklider](/J._C._R._Licklider) was already dreaming up these grand networking ideas. Like sketching constellations in the dark.
*   **1960–1964:** Meanwhile, over at [RAND](/RAND), they were cooking up their own networking concepts. Different paths, same destination, I suppose.
*   **1962–1964:** The [ARPA](/DARPA) boys were also tossing around ideas for networking. A lot of thinking, not much doing yet.
*   **1965:** The [NPL network](/NPL_network) concepts started to take shape. A flicker of something concrete.
*   **1966:** The [Merit Network](/Merit_Network) was born. Another node in the nascent web.
*   **1967:** Plans for [ARPANET](/ARPANET) began. The beast was stirring.
*   **1967:** The [Symposium on Operating Systems Principles](/Symposium_on_Operating_Systems_Principles) happened. A gathering of minds, perhaps before the real storm hit.
*   **1969:** The NPL network, followed by ARPANET, actually started sending their first packets. The first whispers across the void.
*   **1970:** The [Network Information Center](/InterNIC) (NIC) was established. Someone had to keep track of the chaos.
*   **1971:** [Tymnet](/Tymnet) emerged, a switched-circuit network. More pathways being forged.
*   **1972:** Merit Network's packet-switched network went live. It was becoming a reality, however clunky.
*   **1972:** The [Internet Assigned Numbers Authority](/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority) (IANA) was set up. Someone had to assign the numbers, the addresses.
*   **1973:** The [CYCLADES](/CYCLADES) network was demonstrated. Another piece of the puzzle.
*   **1973:** Development on the [PARC Universal Packet](/PARC_Universal_Packet) began. More building blocks.
*   **1974:** The specification for the [Transmission Control Program](/Transmission_Control_Program) was published. The language of communication was being defined.
*   **1975:** [Telenet](/Telenet) launched, a commercial packet-switched network. The business of connecting began.
*   **1976:** The [X.25](/X.25) protocol was approved and rolled out on [public data networks](/Public_data_network). Standards, however dreary, were taking hold.
*   **1978:** [Minitel](/Minitel) made its debut. A precursor, perhaps, to the screen-obsessed world we inhabit.
*   **1979:** The [Internet Activities Board](/Internet_Architecture_Board) (IAB) was formed. The custodians of the burgeoning network.
*   **1980:** [USENET](/Usenet) started using [UUCP](/UUCP) for news. Early forms of online communities.
*   **1980:** The [Ethernet](/Ethernet) standard was introduced. The physical pathways were getting clearer.
*   **1981:** [BITNET](/BITNET) was established. Another network joining the fray.

##### Merging the networks and creating the Internet:

*   **1981:** The [Computer Science Network](/CSNET) (CSNET) was founded. More academic connections.
*   **1982:** The [TCP/IP](/Internet_protocol_suite) protocol suite was formalized. The lingua franca of the internet was agreed upon.
*   **1982:** The [Simple Mail Transfer Protocol](/Simple_Mail_Transfer_Protocol) (SMTP) was developed. Email was becoming a thing.
*   **1983:** The [Domain Name System](/Domain_Name_System) (DNS) arrived. No more memorizing IP addresses, thankfully.
*   **1983:** [MILNET](/MILNET) split off from ARPANET. The military decided to go its own way.
*   **1984:** The [OSI Reference Model](/OSI_model) was released. A theoretical framework, as they like to do.
*   **1985:** The first ['.COM' domain name](/Domain_names) was registered. The commercialization had begun.
*   **1986:** The [NSFNET](/National_Science_Foundation_Network) was established, initially with 56 kbit/s links. A backbone for research.
*   **1986:** The [Internet Engineering Task Force](/Internet_Engineering_Task_Force) (IETF) was formed. The engineers of the digital world.
*   **1987:** [UUNET](/UUNET) was founded. Commercial providers started appearing.
*   **1988:** NSFNET got a speed upgrade to 1.5 Mbit/s (T1). Faster, but still glacial by today's standards.
*   **1988:** The infamous [Morris worm](/Morris_worm) wreaked havoc. The first real taste of internet insecurity.
*   **1988:** The complete [Internet protocol suite](/Internet_protocol_suite) was finalized. The core rules were set.
*   **1989:** The [Border Gateway Protocol](/Border_Gateway_Protocol) (BGP) was introduced. Routing traffic between networks.
*   **1989:** [PSINet](/PSINet) was founded, paving the way for commercial traffic. The floodgates were opening.
*   **1989:** The [Federal Internet Exchanges (FIX East|FIXes)](/Federal_Internet_Exchange) were established. Points of connection.
*   **1990:** [GOSIP](/Government_Open_Systems_Interconnection_Profile) was released, but notably *without* [TCP/IP](/Internet_protocol_suite). A brief detour.
*   **1990:** ARPANET was decommissioned. Its mission was complete.
*   **1990:** [Advanced Network and Services](/Advanced_Network_and_Services) (ANS) was founded. More infrastructure.
*   **1990:** UUNET/Alternet started allowing commercial traffic. The internet was becoming a marketplace.
*   **1990:** The [Archie search engine](/Archie_(search_engine)) emerged. Early attempts to find things in the vastness.
*   **1991:** The [Wide area information server](/Wide_area_information_server) (WAIS) was developed. A way to access information.
*   **1991:** [Gopher](/Gopher_(protocol)) arrived. A precursor to the web, a menu-driven system.
*   **1991:** The [Commercial Internet eXchange](/Commercial_Internet_eXchange) (CIX) was formed. Facilitating commercial exchange.
*   **1991:** ANS CO+RE allowed commercial traffic. More access for businesses.
*   **1991:** The [World Wide Web](/World_Wide_Web) (WWW) was released. The game-changer.
*   **1992:** NSFNET got a significant upgrade to 45 Mbit/s (T3). Speed was increasing.
*   **1992:** The [Internet Society](/Internet_Society) (ISOC) was established. A global body for the internet.
*   **1993:** [Classless Inter-Domain Routing](/Classless_Inter-Domain_Routing) (CIDR) was introduced. A way to manage IP addresses more efficiently.
*   **1993:** InterNIC was established. More administrative structures.
*   **1993:** [AOL](/AOL) added [USENET](/Usenet) access. Bringing the internet to the masses, albeit in a walled garden.
*   **1993:** The [Mosaic web browser](/NCSA_Mosaic) was released. The first widely popular graphical browser. The web became accessible.
*   **1994:** The first full-text web search engines appeared. The quest for information intensified.
*   **1994:** The [North American Network Operators' Group](/North_American_Network_Operators%27_Group) (NANOG) was established. Network professionals organizing.

##### Commercialization, privatization, broader access leads to the modern Internet:

*   **1995:** A new internet architecture emerged, with commercial [ISPs](/Internet_service_provider) connecting at [NAPs](/Network_Access_Point). The privatization was complete.
*   **1995:** NSFNET was decommissioned. The government backbone was no longer needed.
*   **1995:** [GOSIP](/GOSIP) was updated to finally allow [TCP/IP](/Internet_protocol_suite). A belated embrace.
*   **1995:** The [very high-speed Backbone Network Service (vBNS)](/Very_high-speed_Backbone_Network_Service) was launched. Pushing the boundaries of speed.
*   **1995:** [IPv6](/IPv6) was proposed. The next generation of IP addresses, a necessary expansion.
*   **1996:** [AOL](/AOL) shifted its pricing model from hourly to monthly. Making internet access more predictable, and for many, more affordable.
*   **1998:** The [Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICANN)](/ICANN) was created. A new entity to manage the internet's core identifiers.
*   **1999:** [IEEE 802.11b](/IEEE_802.11) wireless networking standards emerged. Untethering the internet.
*   **1999:** [Internet2](/Internet2)/[Abilene Network](/Abilene_Network) was established. A high-performance network for research and education.
*   **1999:** vBNS+ offered broader access. Expanding the reach of high-speed networking.
*   **2000:** The [Dot-com bubble](/Dot-com_bubble) burst. The speculative frenzy came to an abrupt, messy end.
*   **2001:** New top-level domain names were activated. Expanding the naming space.
*   **2001:** The [Code Red I](/Code_Red_(computer_worm)), [Code Red II](/Code_Red_II), and [Nimda](/Nimda) worms caused widespread disruption. A stark reminder of the internet's vulnerabilities.
*   **2003:** The UN World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS) phase I took place. The genesis of this entire discussion.
*   **2003:** The [National LambdaRail](/National_LambdaRail) was founded. More advanced networking initiatives.
*   **2004:** The [UN Working Group on Internet Governance (WGIG)](/Working_Group_on_Internet_Governance) was formed. The debate over control began to heat up.
*   **2005:** WSIS phase II convened. The follow-up, the attempt to iron out the details.
*   **2006:** The first meeting of the [Internet Governance Forum](/Internet_Governance_Forum) was held. A platform for dialogue, however fraught.
*   **2010:** The first internationalized country code top-level domains were registered. Expanding the global reach of domain names.
*   **2012:** [ICANN](/ICANN) began accepting applications for new generic top-level domain names. A significant expansion of the domain name system.
*   **2013:** The [Montevideo Statement on the Future of Internet Cooperation](/Montevideo_Statement_on_the_Future_of_Internet_Cooperation) was issued. More declarations, more statements.
*   **2014:** The [NetMundial international Internet governance proposal](/NetMundial_Initiative) was put forth. Another attempt at shaping the future.
*   **2016:** [ICANN](/ICANN)'s contract with the U.S. Dept. of Commerce ended, and [IANA](/Internet_Assigned_Numbers_Authority) oversight transitioned to the global internet community. A symbolic shift.

##### Examples of Internet services:

The internet isn't just pipes and protocols; it's the services built upon them. And there have been… a lot.

*   **1989:** [AOL](/AOL) started as a dial-up service provider, offering email, instant messaging, and a web browser. The early gateway for many.
*   **1990:** The [IMDb](/IMDb) (Internet Movie Database) was launched. Cataloging cinema, online.
*   **1994:** [Yahoo!](/Yahoo) began as a web directory. Organizing the burgeoning web.
*   **1995:** [Amazon](/Amazon_(company)) launched as an online retailer. The start of e-commerce as we know it.
*   **1995:** [eBay](/EBay) started as an online auction and shopping site. Peer-to-peer commerce found a home.
*   **1995:** [Craigslist](/Craigslist) emerged, offering classified advertisements. Local commerce, digitized.
*   **1995:** [AltaVista](/AltaVista) became a prominent search engine. Another tool to navigate the digital ocean.
*   **1996:** [Outlook (formerly Hotmail)](/Outlook.com) offered free web-based email. Making email accessible to everyone.
*   **1996:** [RankDex](/Baidu) search engine was introduced. More algorithms for searching.
*   **1997:** [Google Search](/Google_Search) was launched. The behemoth began its ascent.
*   **1997:** [Babel Fish](/Babel_Fish_(website)) offered automatic translation. Breaking down language barriers, however imperfectly.
*   **1998:** [Yahoo Groups (formerly Yahoo! Clubs)](/Yahoo_Groups) provided a space for online communities.
*   **1998:** [PayPal](/PayPal) established itself as an internet payment system. Facilitating online transactions.
*   **1998:** [Rotten Tomatoes](/Rotten_Tomatoes) started as a review aggregator. Collecting opinions on films.
*   **1999:** [2ch](/2channel) launched as an anonymous textboard. A raw, unfiltered space for discussion.
*   **1999:** [i-mode](/I-mode) became a mobile internet service. Bringing the web to phones.
*   **1999:** [Napster](/Napster) pioneered peer-to-peer file sharing. Disrupting the music industry.
*   **2000:** [Baidu](/Baidu) search engine was founded in China. A major player in a different digital landscape.
*   **2001:** [2chan](/Futaba_Channel) emerged as an anonymous imageboard. Similar to 2ch, but with a focus on images.
*   **2001:** [BitTorrent](/BitTorrent) revolutionized peer-to-peer file sharing. Efficiently distributing large files.
*   **2001:** [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), the free encyclopedia, was launched. A collaborative knowledge project.
*   **2003:** [LinkedIn](/LinkedIn) began as a business networking site. Connecting professionals.
*   **2003:** [Myspace](/Myspace) became a dominant social networking site. A brief reign.
*   **2003:** [Skype](/Skype) introduced internet voice calls. Making long-distance communication cheaper.
*   **2003:** The [iTunes Store](/ITunes_Store) launched, legalizing digital music downloads.
*   **2003:** [4chan](/4chan) became an anonymous imageboard. Known for its chaotic and often controversial content.
*   **2003:** [The Pirate Bay](/The_Pirate_Bay) emerged as a [torrent file](/Torrent_file) host. A lightning rod for copyright debates.
*   **2004:** [Facebook](/Facebook) launched as a social networking site. Its rise would eventually eclipse Myspace.
*   **2004:** [Podcast](/Podcast) media file series became popular. On-demand audio content.
*   **2004:** [Flickr](/Flickr) offered image hosting. A platform for photographers.
*   **2005:** [YouTube](/YouTube) launched for video sharing. The explosion of user-generated video content.
*   **2005:** [Reddit](/Reddit) introduced link voting. A community-driven news aggregator.
*   **2005:** [Google Earth](/Google_Earth) provided a virtual globe. Visualizing the world online.
*   **2006:** [Twitter](/Twitter) started as a microblogging platform. Short-form communication took hold.
*   **2007:** [WikiLeaks](/WikiLeaks) began publishing anonymous news and information leaks. A controversial player in information dissemination.
*   **2007:** [Google Street View](/Google_Street_View) launched, offering panoramic street-level imagery.
*   **2007:** The [Kindle](/Amazon_Kindle), an [e-reader](/E-reader), and virtual bookshop were introduced. Digitizing books.
*   **2008:** [Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud](/Amazon_Elastic_Compute_Cloud) (EC2) launched, offering cloud computing services. The rise of the cloud.
*   **2008:** [Dropbox](/Dropbox) provided cloud-based file hosting. Simplifying file synchronization.
*   **2008:** The [Encyclopedia of Life](/Encyclopedia_of_Life) was created, aiming to document all living species. A massive collaborative effort.
*   **2008:** [Spotify](/Spotify) launched as a [DRM-based](/Digital_rights_management) music streaming service. The shift to streaming.
*   **2009:** [Bing](/Microsoft_Bing) search engine entered the market. A challenger to Google.
*   **2009:** [Google Docs](/Google_Docs) offered web-based word processing, spreadsheets, and presentations. Collaboration online.
*   **2009:** [Kickstarter](/Kickstarter) introduced a [threshold pledge system](/Threshold_pledge_system). Crowdfunding gained traction.
*   **2009:** [Bitcoin](/Bitcoin), a [digital currency](/Digital_currency), was introduced. The dawn of cryptocurrencies.
*   **2010:** [Instagram](/Instagram) launched for [photo sharing](/Photo_sharing) and [social networking](/Social_networking). Visual communication amplified.
*   **2011:** [Google+](/Google%2B) attempted to enter the [social networking](/Social_networking) space. A notable failure.
*   **2011:** [Snapchat](/Snapchat) debuted for [photo sharing](/Photo_sharing). Ephemeral messaging.
*   **2012:** [Coursera](/Coursera) launched, offering massive open online courses. Education democratized, sort of.
*   **2016:** [TikTok](/TikTok) emerged for [video sharing](/Video_sharing) and [social networking](/Social_networking). Short-form video dominance.

